
String Methods:



CharAt Method:

Verilen index sayisinin hangi karaktere tekabül ettigini gösteriyor.

  String str = "Wooden Spoon";
        int str1 = str.charAt(4);
        System.out.println(str1);
        = e

Length Method:


it gives you the total number of characters.
it starts counting from '1'

  String str = "Wooden Spoon";
        int str1  = str.length();
        System.out.println(str1);
        = 12


Last index number by using length Method:


it starts counting from '0'

       String str = "Wooden Spoon";
               int str1  = str.length() -1;
               System.out.println(str1);
               = 11




 To Uppercase Method:


 it turns all the lower characters to upper

         String str = "Wooden Spoon";
                str  = str.toUpperCase();
                System.out.println(str);
                = WOODEN SPOON


 To LowerCase Method:


  it turns all the upper characters to lower

           String str = "Wooden Spoon";
                  str  = str.toLowerCase();
                  System.out.println(str);
                 = wooden spoon




  Trim Method:


    it removes the whitespaces from beginning and ending of the sentence

              String str = "     Wooden Spoon     ";
                     str  = str.trim();
                     System.out.println(str);
                   = Wooden Spoon



  IndexOf Method:


      it removes the whitespaces from beginning and ending of the sentence

                String str = "     Wooden Spoon     ";
                       str  = str.trim();
                       System.out.println(str);
                     = Wooden Spoon



                     Daily Questions:


                      The switch statement;
                        when you have more conditions to test it's more readable and easy to use,
                        when you test a single variable for multiple possible values,


                        If else statement;
                        when the condition is based on a range of values, rather than specific values,






   --> equals() method:  is used to check whether 2 string objects are equal to each other(same sequence of characters). It returns boolean "true or false".
   --> equalsIgnoreCase(): compares two strings, ignoring lower case and upper case differences (case sensitivity). It returns boolean as well.
   --> == operator: checks if two objects refer to the same memory location, rather than comparing their values.
   --> compareTo() method: compare two strings of the values of the objects and returns boolean as well.